6.Composition

2025-02-28

Purpose

Addressing these following questions found in Loop_2023_overview.RMD:

  1. How much variation is there in microbial DNA in blood (composition)?
  • Examining replicates of each fraction - do you see the same bacteria across subjects (if no, how do you interpret that.. could hint at heterogeneous.. caveat of how much blood do you need to be representative)
  • Are fractions more similar to each other or to the patient?
  • Looking at beta diversity; how close they cluster to each other
  • Can test using distance matrices
  1. Do certain taxa prefer certain compartments of blood?
  • Beta diversity between fractions
  • Identifying if there are different proportion of samples within each cluster
  • Differential abundance (can only do if specific taxa are found across many samples)

Prop test

Are more samples removed from the screen-negative vs other disease groups? Could be interesting. Will be doing a proportion test and will do a Fischers exact test on it due to the small sample size.

# disease
disease_prop <- data.frame(
  "screen_neg" = c(3, 2, 4, 0),
  "low-grade" = c(4, 3, 3, 3),
  "high-grade" = c(5, 3, 5, 2),
  row.names = c("plasma", "RBC", "BF", "WB"),
  stringsAsFactors = FALSE
)
colnames(disease_prop) <- c("screen_neg", "low-grade", "high-grade")

fisher.test(disease_prop)
## 
##  Fisher's Exact Test for Count Data
## 
## data:  disease_prop
## p-value = 0.8906
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
rm(disease_prop)

No association with health status and successfully sequenced sample.

How many taxa present

ps_nomc <- ps %>% 
  subset_samples(., fraction != "mock_community") %>% 
  subset_samples(., dnase == "no")
ps_nomc <- subset_taxa(ps_nomc, taxa_sums(ps_nomc) >0)

taxa_counts <- ps_nomc@tax_table %>% data.frame()

taxa_counts <- lapply(taxa_counts, unique)
taxa_counts <- lapply(taxa_counts, function(x) x[!is.na(x)]) # removing all NAs from each level

print(lengths(taxa_counts))

Overview - Phylum

ps_n <- transform_sample_counts(ps_nomc,function(x) 100* x/sum(x))

ps_n_phy  <- subset_taxa(ps_n_phy, taxa_sums(ps_n_phy) >0)
mdf_phy <- psmelt(ps_n_phy)

summary_phylum <- mdf_phy %>%
        group_by(Phylum) %>%
        summarise(rank_abundance = sum(Abundance), mean_abundance = mean(Abundance), median_abundance = median(Abundance), min_abundance = min(Abundance), max_abundance = max(Abundance)) %>%
        arrange(desc(rank_abundance)) %>%
        mutate(order = row_number()) %>%
        ungroup()

Just a fun overview at the phylum level. It looks like Firmicutes and Proteobacteria are the main phyla. This is sorted by Firmicutes abundance, so the fractions/patients are distributed throughout. The “unknown” is only a label, since typically a higher resolution is put there, butt his is only at the phylum level.

Bubble plot - Genus

I blasted the sequence that is NA and it maps to virgibacillus

ps_nomc <- ps %>% 
  subset_samples(., fraction != "mock_community") %>%
  subset_samples(., dnase == "no") %>% 
  tax_glom(., "Genus", NArm = FALSE)
ps_nomc <- subset_taxa(ps_nomc, taxa_sums(ps_nomc) >0)
ps_nomc_rel <- transform_sample_counts(ps_nomc, function(x) 100* x/sum(x))

ps_nomc_df <- psmelt(ps_nomc_rel)


hm_df <- ps_nomc_df %>% 
  select(sam_names, Genus, Abundance, fraction) %>% 
  filter(Genus %in% top_all$Genus) %>% 
  data.frame()

hm_df$fraction <- factor(hm_df$fraction, levels = c("plasma", "RBC", "BF", "WB"))
hm_df$Genus[hm_df$Genus == "Clostridium sensu stricto 18"] <- "Clostridium"
hm_df$Genus[hm_df$Genus == "Methylobacterium-Methylorubrum"] <- "Methylobacterium \nMethylorubrum"

bubble_plot <- ggplot(hm_df, aes(x = sam_names, y = Genus)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = Abundance, fill = Genus), alpha = 0.75, shape = 21) + 
  facet_wrap(~fraction, scales = "free_x", nrow = 1) +
  scale_size_continuous(limits = c(0.1, 100), range = c(1,17), breaks = c(1,25,50,75)) + labs( x= "Sample", y = "", size = "Relative \nAbundance (%)", fill = "") + 
  guides(fill = "none") +
  theme(legend.key=element_blank(), 
  axis.text.x = element_blank(), 
  panel.background = element_blank(), panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill = NA), 
  legend.position = "right")
